MCC CSS LOADER — HOW THIS WORKS
----------------------------------------------------------------------
What changed
- We centralized ALL visual styles in `assets/mcc-global.css`.
- We split placement-only rules into 3 layout files:
    • Coffee PDP:   assets/mcc-layout-coffee.css
    • Merch PDP:    assets/mcc-layout-merch.css  (mobile drawer; desktop stays Dawn)
    • Default:      assets/mcc-layout-default.css
- Dawn’s `base.css` stays stock. We override Dawn safely from `mcc-global.css`.

Load order (important)
1) Dawn base.css      → theme defaults
2) mcc-global.css     → our visuals (buttons, variants, quantity, price, titles, etc.)
3) ONE layout file    → grid/placement for the current template (coffee / merch / default)

How the layout is chosen
- We use the page’s `template.suffix`:
    • product.coffee  → loads coffee layout
    • product.merch   → loads merch layout
    • anything else   → loads default layout
- Also add the body class once in `layout/theme.liquid` so layout scopes work:
    <body class="layout-{{ template.suffix | default: 'default' }}">

Where to put new styles
- Visuals (colors, borders, fonts, component skins):  mcc-global.css
- Placement (grids, widths, sticky, show/hide by breakpoint):  the relevant mcc-layout-*.css
- Per-layout visual tweaks (e.g., button color): keep them in mcc-global.css, scoped like:
    .layout-merch .btn.primary { /* tweak */ }

Migration notes
- Remove per-section <style> blocks and old CSS includes over time.
- If something still links an old CSS asset, keep a tiny stub asset that `@import`s mcc-global.css
  so you don’t get 404s during cutover.

Adding another layout later
- Create `assets/mcc-layout-<name>.css`, then add a `{% when '<name>' %}` branch below
  and assign a `product.<name>.json` template to products in Admin.

Troubleshooting
- If changes don’t appear, confirm:
    • this snippet is included in <head> (layout/theme.liquid)
    • template suffix matches your file (e.g., “coffee”, “merch”)
    • body class is present on <body> (see above)
